0been%20told%20to%20put%20your%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Flittle-known-iphone-feature-helped-rescue-lost-hiker-california-2024-2%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EiPhone%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20a%20bowl%20of%20rice%20after%20accidentally%20dropping%20it%20in%20the%20sink%20or%20%E2%80%94%20even%20worse%20%E2%80%94%20toilet%3F%20You%20might%20just%20be%20making%20the%20problem%20worse.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEarlier%20this%20year%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fapple%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EApple%3C%2Fa%3E%20quietly%20published%20new%20guidelines%20on%20what%20to%20do%20when%20water%20gets%20into%20your%20iPhone.%20Typically%2C%20when%20phones%2C%20or%20any%20electronic%20devices%2C%20get%20wet%2C%20one%20common%20course%20of%20action%20is%20to%20put%20them%20in%20uncooked%20rice.%20The%20theory%20is%20that%20the%20raw%20grains%20can%20absorb%20the%20moisture.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20Apple's%20latest%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fsupport.apple.com%2Fen-us%2F102643%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Esupport%20document%3C%2Fa%3E%20discourages%20iPhone%20users%20from%20doing%20that%2C%20saying%20that%20small%20grains%20of%20rice%20could%20actually%20damage%20your%20phone%20if%2C%20say%2C%20particles%20get%20lodged%20into%20the%20ports.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAccording%20to%20Apple%2C%20you%20also%20shouldn't%20try%20to%20dry%20your%20moist%20iPhone%20by%20inserting%20a%20%26quot%3Bforeign%20object%26quot%3B%20like%20a%20cotton%20swab%20or%20paper%20towel%20into%20the%20port%2C%20or%20use%20an%20external%20heat%20source%20like%20a%20blow%20dryer.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EStill%2C%20the%20updated%20guidelines%20offer%20a%20few%20suggestions%20on%20what%20users%20can%20safely%20do.%20For%20example%2C%20if%20you%20plug%20your%20iPhone%20into%20a%20wall%20outlet%20with%20a%20lightning%20accessory%20and%20a%20%26quot%3BLiquid%20Detected%26quot%3B%20alert%20appears%2C%20immediately%20unplug%20the%20cable%20from%20b